article.headline: Alabama hits 7 of 8 3-pointers in first half
article.linkText: Vice on target in 'Bama's upset of BYU
article.story:
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Beth Vice scored 15 points and led
Alabama's torrid 3-point shooting in the first half Saturday in a
70-59 win over Brigham Young (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 24 AP).

	   Alabama (8-2) hit 7 of 8 3-pointers in the first half en route
to a 43-29 halftime lead. Vice, who celebrated her 23rd birthday
Saturday, was 3-for-3 on 3s in the first half.

	   BYU (6-3) stayed close through the first 10 minutes of the game,
when the two teams combined to hit their first 13 3-pointers.

Alabama was 7-for-7 on 3-pointers and BYU 6-for-6 in that stretch.

	   BYU, led by Erin Thorn with 16 points and Julie Sullivan with
15, missed all 12 of its 3-pointers in the second half.

	   Alabama hit nearly 61 percent of its shots in the first half,
but then hit just 6 of 28 shots (21 percent) in the second half.
The Tide also went more than 10 minutes in the second half without
a field goal. Still, BYU could not capitalize and got no closer
than 10 points in the final 20 minutes.

	   BYU scored nine straight points to get within 54-44 with 5:26
left in the game. Alabama continued to miss, but the first half
deficit proved too much for the equally cold-shooting Cougars to
overcome.

	   Alabama scored its final 13 points from the free throw line as
BYU repeatedly fouled in the final two minutes.

	   "That's probably about as good as we can play," Alabama coach
Rick Moody said of his team's first half offense. Moody attributed
the Tide's second half shooting problems to fatigue -- Alabama had
just eight players available -- and Albuquerque's mile high
altitude.

	   "Now I understand why this is a very difficult place to play,"
Moody said. "We came out with a tremendous amount of energy and
intensity in the first half and The Pit took its toll. The second
half was tough on both teams."
